<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Spared by Y2K Bug at New Year's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Russia spent the New Year's with
no strike of the much feared millennium bug, the country's Y2K
command center announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"There have been no data on failures and disconnection of
computer systems from the prompt-action headquarters of ministries,
departments, and territories of the Russian Federation," the
Moscow-base center said.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear Power Engineering Minister Yevgeny Adamov also said
that all major facilities of the industry have overcome transition
to 2000 well.
</P>
<P>
All nine nuclear power stations as well as other sectors of the
country's power grid worked in line with their operational
procedures, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Supreme Commander of Russia's Strategic Missile
Troops Vladimir Yakovlev reported a bug-free entrance to the New
Year of the country's formidable nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
"As we promised, our troops prepared for solving the problem
2000 reliably, and we now report that our work was not in vain:
there have been no faults," Yakovlev said.
</P>
<P>
Russia, the world's largest country that spans 11 time zones,
also saw its fleet of some 300 satellites operating smoothly
without the bug, which could fool a computer to interpret the year
2000 as 1000 or 1900. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
