<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Presses Russia Again For Chechnya Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Saturday that it
had again urged Moscow to find a negotiated end to the Chechen war
under Russia's new acting president, Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook told BBC radio that he had spoken
to his Russian counterpart, Igor Ivanov, by telephone on Friday
after Yeltsin handed over power to Putin, and had urged a peaceful
solution to the Chechen crisis.
</P>
<P>
He also said that he thought Russian President Boris Yeltsin
had taken everyone by surprise when he announced on New Year's Eve
that he was resigning in favor of his prime minister Putin.
</P>
<P>
"I put it to him (Ivanov) that given this change in the
political face at the top, that this would be a good time to set
in motion the political process we have been urging upon Russia,"
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
"Without this political process leading to a settlement there
is going to be no permanent, stable outcome of the conflict in
Chechnya," Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov was "keen to stress that there will be a continuity in
Russian foreign policy and that there will be no shift from the
strategic direction Boris Yeltsin set of strategic engagement with
the outside world," Cook told the BBC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
