<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Continues Assault on Chechen Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian federal troops continued
their assault on rebels in the breakaway republic of Chechnya
Saturday, with fierce battles reported in Grozny, the regional
capital.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, who took over as Russia's acting
president following Boris Yeltsin's resignation Friday, arrived in
Gudermes, Chechnya, early Saturday and presented awards to
soldiers for their valor in fighting the militants.
</P>
<P>
In the ceremony broadcast live to the nation, Putin said their
actions "was not merely the restoration of the country's prestige
and dignity" but "putting an end to the breakup of Russia."
</P>
<P>
A senior Russian military official said Saturday that federal
forces had killed scores of rebels in Chechnya since Friday,
including several rebel commanders.
</P>
<P>
"The enemy sustained losses. Eight control points were
destroyed at which there had been so-called field commanders,
among them Abu Barayev, a fairly well-known terrorist," Major-
General Vadim Timchenko, deputy chief of the North Caucasus staff,
told the independent NTV television.
</P>
<P>
"Altogether the enemy lost up to 89 men. And that is in Grozny
alone. We also had losses. Altogether, we lost eight men as killed
and 16 as wounded in that period."
</P>
<P>
The military campaign was launched last September following
armed Chechen incursions into neighboring Daghestan and a series
of apartment bombings that killed some 300 people in Moscow and
two other Russian cities. Authorities have accused Chechen
militants of masterminding the blasts.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Chechnya, Putin said that the completion of
the anti-terrorist operation there would not be timed for any
concrete date, the presidential election day included. The
balloting is reportedly scheduled for March 26.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the federal government's readiness to hold talks
with Chechen leaders, if they denounce terrorism, free hostages
and hand over those suspected of staging the terrorist bombings.
</P>
</TEXT>
