<HEADLINE> Feature: Chicago Ushers in New Millennium with International Dinner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chicago, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Chicago, the third largest U.S.
city located on the shores of Lake Michigan in the heart of
Midwest, ushered in the new millennium with an international
millennium dinner attended by nearly 4000 people from all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
To celebrate the new millennium and the new year, Mayor of
Chicago Richard M. Daley and the municipal government invited 418
guests from 205 countries and regions on earth, one person with a
companion of his or her choice from every nation and region, to
join Chicagoans for the dinner.
</P>
<P>
The guests are not celebrities or dignitaries, but average
working people, such as a mechanic from Guatemala, a bird trainer
from Vietnam, a teacher from Bangladesh, an acrobatics performer
from China and a washing machine repairer from Suriname.
</P>
<P>
"This unique gathering is designed to further an important goal
for the coming millennium: fostering greater knowledge of our
world, and bettering communication between its many and varied
peoples," said a municipal government press release.
</P>
<P>
The evening began with a unique performance in the Arie Crown
Theater -- a showcase of Chicago's best musical, dance and
literary talent. After the performance, the 4,000 international
guests and Chicagoans were treated to the international millennium
dinner at a big hall in the MiCormick Lakeside Center decorated
with more than 400 multicolored resin chandeliers. The special
menu of the American-style feast, developed and prepared by
Chicago-based Levy Restaurants, included roasted lemon chicken and
apple pie cheesecake.
</P>
<P>
"As we look toward a new millennium, we come together as a
global family to break bread and exchange our wishes for the
future of Chicago and the world. Let's work hard to make better
cities, better countries, a better people and a better world."
said Chicago Mayor Richard M. Daley at the dinner. "It is my hope,
that by welcoming two citizens from nearly every country to
Chicago's dinner table, we will create connections between people
that will last well into the next century."
</P>
<P>
The idea of the international millennium dinner, a key
component of the city's three-year celebration, was given by an
Italian man named Dino de Vincenzi through an e-mail when the city
was looking for an idea to celebrate the new millennium in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"I know Chicago is a city made up of immigrants from different
countries, so I think it's a good idea to invite two people from
every country in the world for the millennium gala, said Dino, who
works for the finance division of the municipal government in
Vigevano, a town near Milan. "For the first time in mankind's
history all the countries of the earth sit at the same table,
enjoying the company of one another and giving our hopes of peace
and brotherhood in a middle-of-the night toast."
</P>
<P>
"It's like a dream came true to celebrate the new millennium
here," said Knox Mshumayeli Nxumalo, a guest from Swaziland. "we
have seen too many wars in this century, my best hope for next
century is peace."
</P>
<P>
Dancing and singing went late into night before they started
the countdown for the new millennium. At midnight, the whole sky
was lit up like daytime by the largest extraordinary fireworks
display in the city's history.
</P>
<P>
Besides the millennium dinner and the fireworks display,
Chicago also greeted the year 2000 with a "Dance 'till the Dawn of
the New Millennium" -- a 2000-Minute Party from 9 a.m. on December
31, 1999 to 6:20 p.m. on January 1, 2000. More than 200 Chicago
dance groups danced together with Chicagoans and visitors in
nearly 100 locations, at museums, hotels, dance clubs, community
centers and attractions.
</P>
<P>
"We are excited to share our great city with our honored
guests," said Dorothy Coyle, Director of the Chicago Office of
Tourism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
