<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Y2K Problem Reported in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The South African
government announced that no Y2K-related problems have been
reported in the country during the 12 hours ending at noon on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"All major mission critical systems such as transport,
communications, electricity, water, health services and emergency
services are reported to be operating normally," said Provincial
and Local Government Minister Sydney Mufamadi.
</P>
<P>
"We have only received a few reports of disruption of some of
these services -- such as electricity -- but those were because of
weather conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Louis Buys, head of the Provincial and Local Department's Y2K
disaster management center, said some local councils, mostly in
rural areas, had not reported on their Y2K status, but officials
had managed to confirm via other channels that all systems in
these areas were up and running.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Airports Company of South Africa, the country's
airports authority, said it had successfully navigated the
transition to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
According to government Y2K spokesman Fred Barron, Y2K problem
is not a single event limited to the changeover from 1999 to 2000,
many computer systems can only be checked for compliance when
businesses re-open after the holiday period.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the Y2K center would continue monitoring the
situation 24 hours a day until at least January 5, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
