<HEADLINE> Nigeria Resolved to Cut Debt, Combat Corruption in New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo said Saturday that external debt reduction and anti-
corruption campaign are high on his country's agenda in the new
century.
</P>
<P>
He said in his new millennium message that Nigeria could not
score significant economic growth with a huge debt of about 30
million U.S. dollars. Nigeria is now Africa's biggest debt nation.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the people of Nigeria to support the
government's anti-corruption campaign.
</P>
<P>
Anti-corruption is a centerpiece of Obasanjo's domestic
policies. The first bill he sent to the National Assembly, the
country's top legislature, is an anti-corruption act.
</P>
<P>
If Nigeria wants to make a difference in the new millennium,
its people must refrain form violence and learn to be tolerant,
the president added.
</P>
<P>
The rising trend of ethnic clashes, especially in the oil
producing Niger delta region has long been a trouble for the new
civilian government, which took over the 15-year uninterrupted
military rule last May.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo's speech came hours after the conclusion of many over-
night Millennium Celebrations throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people gathered at Eagle Square in downtown Abuja
from last night until early this morning, to attend a massive
concert and dancing party, which culminated at mid-night in
countdown and fireworks shows, to mark the arrival of the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo and his wife, along with some ministers of his
government, attended the event.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, Nigeria's largest city and commercial capital, many
people waited in a square for the coming of the new century,
accompanied by pop bands and singers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
