<HEADLINE> Hijacked Indian Plane Arrives In New Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Airlines A-300
Airbus, which endured an eight-day hijacking drama, reached here
Saturday from Kandahar, Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The plane could not arrive on Friday along with two other
aircraft which took all the released passengers and the Indian
delegation headed by External Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh back
to the country following an agreement reached between the
hijackers and New Delhi on the release of 155 hostages in exchange
for three militants.
</P>
<P>
Official sources here said the repair work was completed last
night but the plane could not depart on time due to heavy fog in
New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The plane suffered several minor snags due to the absence of
regular maintenance during the grueling journey it undertook from
Kathmandu on December 24, which ended the next day at Kandahar via
India's border town of Amritsar and Abu Dhabi of the UAE.
</P>
<P>
The co-pilot of the ill-fated plane, Rajender Kumar, defended
the government's decision to secure the release of the hostages in
exchange for three militants, saying it was the only possible
option available with the government in the given circumstances.
</P>
<P>
Kumar said the plane was hijacked when he was flying it but
soon after the incident, captain Sharan took over. 
</P>
