<HEADLINE> Over 840 Injured in Millennium Celebration in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- There were 795 cases of
firecracker-related injuries and 47 cases of stray bullets in
millennium celebrations in the Philippines by Saturday morning,
said an official.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Alberto Romualdez told reporters here Saturday
that the surveillance period started 10 days ago and will end on
January 4, and 68 hospitals are involved in this surveillance
activity.
</P>
<P>
By 09:00 (01:00 GMT) Saturday, 795 people had been injured by
firecrackers and 47 by stray bullets, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our overall assessment is that the increase in injuries due to
fireworks is not as high as we feared. We would like to think that
this has been due to the cooperative effort among all of the
agencies concerned including the media to properly inform our
people of way to handle fireworks," the official pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said that last year there were 547 firecracker-related
injuries and 24 cases of stray bullets in new year celebrations.
</P>
<P>
But he said there could have been a lot more injuries this year
if people had not been reminded to take extra care.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there were five festivity-related fires in Manila in
the last 24 hours, killing nine people, according to the
Philippine News Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
