<HEADLINE> No Y2K-Related Problems Reported in Ethiopia: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- There has been no report of
Y2K-related problems in Ethiopia since December 31, an official of
the Rollover Command Center (RCC) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian Airlines said earlier that it is currently
operating effectively as the Y2K problems were not identified in
its network.
</P>
<P>
The airlines of various countries are coming to Ethiopia and do
business as usual, EAL public relations chief Abbamilki Abbagerro
said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has made full preparations to guard against what was
called the computer millennium bug that distorts all the documents
in the computer when the year 2000 comes.
</P>
<P>
In addition to general precautions, the EAL also established a
temporary office known as the Roller Command Center (RCC) to serve
as focal point for Y2K-related problems during the transition.
</P>
<P>
The office, which has been operating since December 31, 1999,
is in charge of collecting Y2K-related information from internal
and external sources and disseminating the information to all
institutions concerned, EAL officials said.
</P>
<P>
All employees, including field office staff, are expected to
inform any Y2K-related event with a potential impact on Ethiopian
operation to the RCC immediately, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
