<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Y2K Disruption Happens in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Iran announced Saturday that it
did not face any problem caused by the millenium bug (Y2K) as it
entered the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The Millennium Information Dissemination Committee (MIDC) at the
Interior Ministry said that the condition at all parts and
organizations of the country were reported normal.
</P>
<P>
The country's electricity, water, energy and communication
networks were working normally without any problems during the
year-changing hours, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem stems from the fact that old computers
recognizes a year only by the last two digits. When the clock of
the computer ticks to the year 2000, the computer will take it as
the year 1900, thus causing confusion in all calculations and
operations which take a date into account.
</P>
<P>
The flag carrier Iran Air resumed its domestic and international
flights at 06:00 a.m. local time (0230 GMT) after a suspension of
over 10 hours due to the concerns on the Y2K problem.
</P>
<P>
The MIDC also said the refineries and all institutions
affiliated to the Iranian Oil Ministry are working normally after
arrival of the year 2000, and loading of oil tankers is going on
according to predetermined schedule without any halt.
</P>
<P>
Precautionary measures have been taken to prevent unexpected
incidents at the institutions and the Oil Ministry had embarked on
storing fuel in case of any problems cropping up.
</P>
<P>
Iranian officials have warned of possible disruption in energy,
communications, transportation and other services due to the Y2K
problem and the cabinet announced January 1 as a public holiday to
prevent possible crisis caused by Y2K bug.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
