<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search for Missing Plane Underway In Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Turkish rescue team are still
searching the missing Equatorial Guinea cargo plane around Mt.
Goynuk, north Turkey, reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-made Antonov-28, with six crew members on a flight
from Ukraine to Iran, went missing shortly after it requested
permission to land in Ankara to refuel on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the plane's disappearance, Turkish Naval Forces (DKK)
began to search at sea and land, but no wreckage has been found.
</P>
<P>
The rescue efforts, initiated at the spot where the aircraft
gave its SOS call, were carried out by DKK helicopters, planes and
frigates.
</P>
<P>
An announcement from the General Directorate of State Airports
said that the plane was first detected by civilian radars at an
altitude of 3,200 feet and cruising at a speed of 85 nautical
miles.
</P>
<P>
It maintained that the altitude reading indicated that the plane
was losing control owing to technical failure.
</P>
<P>
During an interview with the private channel NTV, Turkish
Transport Minister Enis Oksuz said that the matter was very
important. "We regard it as a suspicious plane," he added. However,
there was no report on what cargo the plane was carrying.
</P>
<P>
The Ukraine Embassy in Ankara declined to give explanations of
the plane's mission, but expressed thanks to the Turkish rescue
efforts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
