<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SIA Resumes Normal Flight Schedules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Airlines (SIA)
Saturday announced that it has activated plans to resume normal
schedules as it has experienced no problems following the rollover
into year 2000.
</P>
<P>
SIA canceled 100 flights and re-scheduled 40 others scheduled
for the period from December 30 to January 1 in an effort to avoid
having aircraft in the air at midnight on December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS) affirmed
in its press release at noon that all financial institutions in
Singapore have fully tested their systems Saturday morning and no
Y2K-related problems have been reported.
</P>
<P>
MAS said financial service providers are carrying out full
systems checks Saturday and mock trading sessions are being
conducted by the Singapore Exchange (SGX) and member firms in
preparation for the first trading day of the new year.
</P>
<P>
Thus far, MAS added, SGX has successfully completed mock
trading for the security market and comprehensive systems tests
for the derivatives market are proceeding without hitches.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the morning, the Infocomm Development Authority of
Singapore announced that Singapore's government systems and
critical infrastructure service providers in finance, utilities,
telecommunications, transportation and health care made a smooth
crossover into the new millennium without experiencing any Y2K-
related troubles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
