<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Survives Y2K Scare: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has survived
initially the millennium bug scare with basic services going on
unhampered after the rollover date, the Y2K Contingency Task Force
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
National Security Adviser Alexander Aguirre, chairman of the
Y2K Contingency Task Force, said, however, that monitoring will
continue up to January 3, the first weekday of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We are optimistic that our initial success will continue. We
are still going to monitor the other sectors, but (we will know)
whether it's really completely OK or not when we have our regular
office hours on Monday," Aguirre said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
The Aguirre task force is in charge of drawing up plans to make
sure that the millennium bug, a built-in flaw in old computer
systems that prevents them from correctly interpreting dates from
January 1, 2000 onward, does not disrupt basic services.
</P>
<P>
Since 1998, the government has prepared for the bug, with
President Joseph Estrada creating the Presidential Commission on
Year 2000 Compliance to make sure that mission-critical sectors
are not affected by it. These sectors are telecommunication,
transportation, finance, manufacturing, government services,
health care and utilities.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the commission and the task force, the government
also established a Y2K Action Center for the purpose of responding
to emergencies related to the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K Action Center started operating on a 24-hour basis last
December 28. It has links with other agencies such as the National
Disaster Coordinating Council to ensure prompt response and has
made available its hotlines to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
