<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, January 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese officials said Saturday that some minor
malfunctions were reported at nuclear power plants as the new year
started, but the country's key sectors have not experienced any
major problems related to the millennium computer bug.
</P>
<P>
"The malfunctions are not of the nature that would immediately
affect people's lives," Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Fukushiro
Nukaga told a news conference. Malfunctions were reported at the
Shiga nuclear power plant in Ishikawa Prefecture, west of Tokyo,
but the system used for sending data to government ministries and
company headquarters during emergencies failed to display the
information. (Japan-Y2K-Nuclear Power)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Acting Russian President Vladimir Putin flew to the
breakaway Chechnya republic on Saturday to award medals to Russian
soldiers who are fighting rebels there.
</P>
<P>
A live television coverage showed Putin in Gudermes, east of
the regional capital Grozny, encouraging soldiers to fight for an
intact Russian Federation. (Russia-Chechnya-Putin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea Saturday spoke highly of Russian President
Boris Yeltsin's contribution to the world peace and expected that
Acting President Vladmir Putin will continue the reform.
</P>
<P>
"We deem highly Yeltin's contribution to Russia's democratic
and economic development and to the world peace," said the Foreign
Affair and Trade Ministry in a commentary issued Saturday morning
on Yeltsin's resignation. "We hope that Russia will continue on
with its reform policy under the leadership of Acting President
Putin and that the upcoming presidential election will provide an
important opportunity for democratic advancement and political
stability of Russia," the ministry said. (SKorea-Russia-Politics)
</P>
