<HEADLINE> Ugandan Rebels Kills 9 On Eve of New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Rebels of Lord's Resistance Army
(LRA), a major rebel group operating in northern Uganda, killed
nine people in their surprise attack on Gulu town on the eve of
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The LRA rebels made a daring attack on the official residence
of the Resident District Commissioner Peter Odok w'Ochieng and
ambushed a pick-up truck, the New Vision daily reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They reportedly attacked the vehicle at Loyoboo, 13 kms on the
Gulu-Kitgum road in the afternoon. This is the first attack on
Gulu town after they sneaked into Uganda from bases in southern
Sudan on December 22, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The LRA rebels, spearheaded by Joseph Kony have been fighting
against the government since 1986 when the ruling National
Resistance Movement led by President Yoweri Museveni came to power
after a five-year guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
They kill, maim, loot and abduct just to tarnish the image of
the government. They have allegedly abducted more than 10,000
children during their attacks in the northern region.
</P>
<P>
Reports here said that the peace accord signed by President
Museveni and his Sudanese counterpart Omar al-Bashir in Nairobi on
December 8 squeezes the rebels' space for survival and brings new
hope for the resolution of the issue.
</P>
<P>
Uganda and Sudan have been accusing each other of backing
rebels operating on their respective territories. Their relations
were severed in April 1995.
</P>
<P>
The recently signed peace pact is a good sign toward the ending
of this hostility. Both countries promised to resume full
diplomatic relations by the end of February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
