<HEADLINE> First Macao Tourists at Gongbei Customs Checkpoint in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The first 10 tourists of Macao
arriving at Gongbei Customs Checkpoint of Zhuhai, south China's
Guangdong Province, on the first day of the year 2000 were
presented with bunches of fresh flowers today.
</P>
<P>
Customs workers at the checkpoint also gave a certificate to a
Macao resident who hit the checkpoint before all others in the
group early this morning, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
Macao was returned to the motherland on December 20, 1999.
Since then, the number of passenger arrivals and departures at the
Gongbei Customs Checkpoint has been growing enormously, with the
daily number set at more than 100,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The volume will continue to climb as many residents from Macao
go to visit relatives mostly in areas of neighboring Guangdong
Province during the New Year holidays.
</P>
<P>
Business at a long-distance bus station near the customs
checking building is very brisk due to the increased inflow of
tourists from Macao, said local sources.  
</P>
</TEXT>
