<HEADLINE> Ghana Enters New Millennium Without Y2K Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 1, (Xinhua) -- Ghana entered the new
millenniumAccra.
</P>
<P>
Commander Pius Griffiths, deputy Minister of Communications in
charge of the Y2K office, told the Ghana News Agency 90 minutes
after midnight that his office had not received any reports of
computer bug problems.
</P>
<P>
Most of the country's major institutions, including the Ghana
Civil Aviation Authority, Electricity Company, Ghana Water
Company and Ghana Telecom have continued to function without any
hitch.
</P>
<P>
Other institutions such as the electronic media houses,
especially radio and television carried live transmission of
various programs into the new year without any interruption.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy, for now, we have not received any negative
reports," Griffiths said, adding that his office was still
collecting data from across the country.
</P>
<P>
The usually busy Kotoka International Airport remained quiet
with no schedule flights.
</P>
<P>
The National carrier, Ghana Airways, cancelled its commercial
flights during the critical period of December 31 and January 1.
</P>
<P>
It said although it is Y2K compliant, it could not trust that
other flight information regions are compliant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
