<HEADLINE> Chinese Sports Enthusiasts Jog, Dance on New Year's Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Kunming of southwestern China, more than 10,000 people ran
some two kilometers along downtown section's Dongfeng Road, waving
flags which read "Sports for All to Improve People's Health" and "
Good Health Benefit Generations".
</P>
<P>
Retired athletes including former national marathon champion
Zhong Huandi led the mass jog.
</P>
<P>
In Xining of western Qinghai Province, more than 4,000 people
from various nationalities jogged in the annual New Year's Day Run
Saturday morning. Sports fans up in their 70s in age joined in
others in men's five kilometers and women's seven km races as well
as a 4.4km run for the master runners.
</P>
<P>
In Chengdu, capital of southwestern Sichuan Province, 12,000
students, workers, farmers and company employees took the streets
for the annual New Year's Day race. Participants ranging up to 78
years to only six in age joined in the speed event, jogs and cycle
races to the entertainment of spectators and themselves.
</P>
<P>
While in Dalian of northeastern Liaoning Province, the giant
Olympic Square was filled with sports enthusiasts in the morning
hours of the historical weekend. People played tennis, practiced
Taijiquan (hollow boxing) and dragon dance.
</P>
<P>
Among those devoted to the traditional dance of Yangge was 72-
year-old Zhou Houlan. Having practiced the colorful fold dance
ever since 1950s, the most persistent member of a dance group
based in the area is fit and healthy. Despite of her
participation in the New Year's Eve celebrations late into the
early hours on Saturday, she appeared in the practices in the
morning.
</P>
<P>
"I usher in the new century with Yangge," she said. 
</P>
