<HEADLINE> HK Enters the Year 2000 Free From Y2K Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has safely entered
the year 2000 without a single Y2K failure reported, according to
reports from all major sectors Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Since the arrival of 2000, the Marine Department went on full
alert during the millennium rollover, and no Y2K-induced incident
has been reported, a spokesman for the department said. Sea
traffic within Hong Kong waters was closely monitored to ensure
navigational safety, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Office of the Telecommunications Authority (OFTA) announced
Saturday morning that the telecommunications sector of Hong Kong
has successfully rolled over to Y2K.
</P>
<P>
"As at 8:30 a.m. Saturday, we have not received any Y2K-induced
failure reports from telecommunications service providers," said a
spokesman from OFTA. "The operation of the telecommunications
services in Hong Kong had not been affected by any Y2K problem
during the rollover."
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Monetary Authority said at 7.00 a.m. Saturday
that it has received reports on the first full round of wellness
checks on all the major shared system providers to the banking
industry in Hong Kong, including Hong Kong Interbank Clearing Ltd.
All these shared systems are working normally.
</P>
<P>
"We shall continue to monitor the situation closely and shall
be receiving the results of further wellness checks on other
systems from banks over the next two days," said a HKMA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's aviation sector has not received any Y2K failure
report since the arrival of the year 2000. Between midnight and 4:
00 a.m. Saturday, there were six flight movements, five arrivals
and one departure, at the Hong Kong International Airport (HKIA).
</P>
<P>
All of Civil Aviation Department's air traffic control systems
and equipment such as radars, communications facilities and
navigation equipment have been functioning normally since the Y2K
rollover. No glitches were reported by the Airport Authority Hong
Kong and the Hong Kong Air Cargo Terminals Limited.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong moved into the year 2000 without a single Y2K-induced
incident, Deputy Secretary for Information Technology and
Broadcasting Jessie Ting declared Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in the Government's Y2K Press Center
at 2:00 a.m., Ting said the Y2K Central Co-ordinating Center (CCC)
had monitored the rollover since Friday noon working closely with
the 13 co-ordinating centers for essential service sectors.
</P>
<P>
None of them had reported Y2K-induced glitches by 2:00 a.m.,
she said. The sectors covered aviation, broadcasting, energy
supply, environment, fire and emergency services, financial
services, food supply, immigration, port management, public health,
public order, telecommunications and transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
