<HEADLINE> Chiluba Calls for Economic Emancipation of Africa  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Friday urged Africans to shift their struggle to fight for
their economic emancipation in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
In a national address on television and radio on the eve of the
new millennium Chiluba said that now that the entire Africa is
politically independent, "our struggle must shift, we must shift
to economic emancipation. Our theme for this momentous occasion is
'enhancing democracy and national economic development in the new
millennium.'"
</P>
<P>
He urged all Africans to work for Africa's peace and unity.
</P>
<P>
It is imperative that in the new millennium, the gap between
the rich and the poor is narrowed through equitable distribution
of wealth, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is morally indefensible, It is morally unacceptable, that
the poorest of the poor should continue to wallow in the depth of
poverty, in the middle of ostentatious living. We must
deliberately create opportunities for all our citizens, to aspire
for and attain a better standard of life," Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
He said that when Africans enter the new century the basic
foundations for political stability and democratic practice have
been firmly established throughout much of Africa. What Africa now
needs is the economic means to sustain the momentum.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba complained that Western industrialized countries have
failed to underwrite Africa's democracy.
</P>
<P>
He identified growing external debt burden and the
disadvantageous terms of trade as the obstacles to continue to
hinder growth and development of the African continent.
</P>
<P>
The president, Therefore, called for debt relief, debt write-
off and development assistance from the international community to
improve the economic circumstances of African countries in the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
The last millennium has been a nightmare for Africa, sometimes
from self inflicted causes, yes, Africa has gone to slumber as the
rest of the global community has moved on to the outer reaches of
universe, Africa has lost valuable time pre-occupied by mundane
issues of daily sustenance, he said.
</P>
<P>
Although Africa lies licking and nursing its wounds from self
inflicted conflicts, the promise of political stability is certain
and although Africa is burdened by the millstone of massive debt,
economic emancipation is more than assured, said Chiluba.
</P>
<P>
"The new millennium must mean a new Africa, free from vices
that hold us down," said the Zambian president.
</P>
<P>
He called on his countrymen to deliberately enhance their
capacities to exploit the technological advances.
</P>
<P>
On the recent coup d'etat in Cote D'ivoire, Chiluba condemned
the military junta for taking power from an elected and legitimate
government of president Henri Konan Bedie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
