<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0445 GMT, January 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Wall Street stocks celebrated the year-end session
with a full slate of records Friday in confidence that the world
financial markets would be free from the Y2K problem when Year
2000 is rolling in.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 44.26 at 11,497.12,
surpassing the record closing high of 11,484.66 points set
Wednesday. The session ended at 1 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor'
s 500 index rose 4.78 at a new high of 1,469.25 and the
technology heavy Nasdaq composite index rose 32.44 at 4.069.31,
topping the record high of 4.041.46 points set Wednesday. (New
york-Stocks-Closing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- The Latin American Economic Commission said
Friday that the share of the agriculture and livestock sector in
the Latin American economy had a trend to diminish by almost 50
percent in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
The study, prepared by Margarita Flores de la Vega, a member of
the commission, said that the sector accounted for 18 percent of
the gross domestic product of the region in mid-1970s, but it
dropped to 8.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However agriculture remains a sector where labor is
concentrated but with low productivity. It cannot reduce the
poverty in the rural area. (L.America-Agriculture)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia's exports in the first 11 months of 1999
dropped by 1.94 percent in value to 44.07 billion U.S.dollars from
the figure recorded for the same period in 1998, according to the
Central Bureau of Statistics. (Indonesia-Exports)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong Friday
affirmed that his country's economy grew 5.6 percent in 1999 and
will expand by between 4.5 to 6.5 percent for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Goh made the statement in his new year message entitled "Into
The Millennium With Confidence.
</P>
<P>
Describing 1999 as a year of consolidation and recovery for
Asia, Goh said Singapore's economy grew 8.2 percent in the fourth
quarter of 1999 and achieved a 5.6 percent growth for 1999 as a
whole. (Singapore-Economy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- India's economy grew by 6 percent during the
second quarter of the current fiscal (July-September) year
compared to a 4.2 percent growth in the corresponding period last
year, the Central Statistical Organization said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth was pushed by robust performance by the
manufacturing and agricultural sectors. (India-Economy)  
</P>
