<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Exports Down in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
While the value of oil and gas exports increased by 19.80
percent to 8.63 billion dollars, that of non-oil and non-gas
exports dropped by 6.09 percent to 35.44 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil and non-gas exports in the first 11 months of 1999
contributed 80.41 percent to the overall exports, or 3.56 percent
less than in the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Oil and gas exports accounted for 19.59 percent of the overall
exports,with 9.15 percent contributed by crude petroleum, 1.87 by
refined oil and 8.57 percent by natural gas.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the country's exports was an indication that part
of its export-oriented industries still relied on the countries of
destination despite the fact that domestic political and economic
conditions were improving, head of the BPS Sugito Suwito said.
</P>
<P>
The bureau also noted that the country's imports during the
period were only 21.83 billion dollars, down by 12.45 percent from
the corresponding period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia enjoyed a surplus of 22.24 billion dollars in its
trade with foreign countries in the January-November period of
1999, Sugito was quoted by the Antara News Agency Saturday as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
