<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Agricultural Productivity Drops, Says Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Latin American
Economic Commission said Friday that the share of the agriculture
and livestock sector in the Latin American economy had a trend to
diminish by almost 50 percent in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
The study, prepared by Margarita Flores de la Vega, a member of
the commission, said that the sector accounted for 18 percent of
the gross domestic product of the region in mid-1970s, but it
dropped to 8.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However agriculture remains a sector where labor is
concentrated but with low productivity. It cannot reduce the
poverty in the rural area.
</P>
<P>
It said in none of the countries in the region the sector
offers employment for less than 10 percent of the total
economically active population. In most cases the occupation
surpasses 20 percent, and in Mexico it is 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Latin American agricultural sector faces the challenge of
introducing better forms of production to peasants of small groups
since there exist noticeable differences between the agricultural
workers in Latin America and those of the United States, Japan and
Israel among others.
</P>
<P>
The study underscores that poverty affects one third of the
population in Latin America, and more than half in the rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
