<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Post-Yeltsin Russia Welcomes New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Russia, with thousands of nuclear-tipped missiles and many
nuclear power plants, was listed in the West as among the
countries most susceptible to the millennium problem. But several
hours into the New Year, there were no reports of any attacks of
the Y2K bug, which fools a computer to interpret the year 2000 as
1000 or 1900.
</P>
<P>
Officially, the world's largest country, which spans 11 time
zones, has not entered the new millennium yet: the State
Commission of Standards has ruled that the third millennium starts
a year later.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, in a televised address to the nation Friday, announced
his decision to step down six months before his term ends in June
and handed his powers to Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, the acting
president.
</P>
<P>
The move was seen as the best New Year present to Putin, who is
already the most popular politician in the post-Soviet Russia.
</P>
<P>
The approval rate of Putin, who took office as premier in
August, skyrocketed from a mere 2 percent to well over 50 percent
amid a popular military campaign against rebels in the breakaway
republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
The offensive, launched in September following armed Chechen
incursions into neighboring Daghestan and a spate of terrorist
bombings that killed over 300 people in Moscow and two other
cities, is till in progress, but federal commanders said the final
stage is nearing its end.
</P>
<P>
In Moscow, revelers flocked to the Red Square, the Pushkin
Square and several other venues to mark the New Year. A light snow
under relatively warm temperature brought more crowds to the
celebrations, although some 80 percent of Russians said in a pre-
New Year's poll that they would celebrate at home.
</P>
<P>
With the economic crisis apparently bottoming out in 1999, many
Muscovites harbor a guarded optimism for the new year.
</P>
<P>
Less than 18 months after the devastating August 1998 ruble
devaluation, a poll conducted a week earlier found that some 42
percent of the Muscovites expect their family's economic condition
will improve next year.
</P>
<P>
It is not a majority, but it is a jump from last year's 27
percent, and beats the previous high of 30 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Russians outside the rich national capital are less sanguine. A
December 17 to December 20 survey of 1,600 people conducted by the
VTsIOM public opinion agency found that only 6 percent thought the
year 2000 would be better than 1999.
</P>
<P>
Five percent said conditions would worsen, while 17 percent
said 2000 would be no worse than 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
