<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Power Plants Malfunctions Reported as Japan Enters 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Japanese officials said Saturday
that some minor malfunctions were reported at nuclear power plants
as the new year started, but the country's key sectors have not
experienced any major problems related to the millennium computer
bug.
</P>
<P>
"The malfunctions are not of the nature that would immediately
affect people's lives," Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Fukushiro
Nukaga told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Malfunctions were reported at the Shiga nuclear power plant in
Ishikawa Prefecture, west of Tokyo, but the system used for
sending data to government ministries and company headquarters
during emergencies failed to display the information.
</P>
<P>
Another alarm went off shortly after midnight at the Onagawa
nuclear power plant in Miyagi Prefecture, northeast of Tokyo, but
operations returned to normal 10 minutes later, according to
government officials.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government is investigating whether the problems
arose from the Y2K computer glitch, Nukaga said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the country's some 2,300 major medical facilities,
including emergency hospitals, reported having no Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Naoyuki Akikusa, chairman of the Japan Electronic
Industry Development Association, told a separate news conference
that none of his 148 companies had reported any problems involving
the Y2K computer bug.
</P>
<P>
But he also advised companies to beware of possible trouble on
Tuesday, the first business day of the year.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who launched a task force
at his office Friday evening to gather information related to the
computer glitch, said early Saturday that no problems arising from
the Y2K bug have been reported in the country's key services.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million people in Japan's public and private
sectors, including 806,000 firefighters, 106,000 police officers,
96,000 members of the Self-Defense Forces and 2,000 civil servants
at government ministries and agencies, went on alert to prepare
for the millennium bug. 
</P>
</TEXT>
