<HEADLINE> No Major Y2K Problem Reported in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- No major problems related to the
feared Y2K computer glitch have been reported in Japan as the
country crossed into 2000, Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi
said here early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Fortunately, there have been no major incidents that would
have a major impact on people's living," Obuchi told a press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Railways, airport services and traffic lights functioned
normally, power stations operated in a stable manner and no
telephone line malfunctions were reported as the clock ticked into
2000, said Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Although there were some connection problems regarding cellular
phones in some areas and international calls to China and the
Philippines, they were related not to the computer glitch but to
the usual flood of calls on New Year's Day, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese prime minister, however, said his government will
continue to look out for problems.
</P>
<P>
More than 2 million people in Japan's public and private
sectors, including 806,000 firefighters, 106,000 police officers,
96,000 members of the Self-Defense Forces and 2,000 civil servants
at government ministries and agencies, went on alert to prepare
for the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
On Friday evening, Obuchi launched a 50-strong task force at
his office to gather information on problems related to the
computer glitch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
