<HEADLINE> China's Easternmost Point Celebrates New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
USU, HEILONGJIANG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Braving freezing cold,
eight soldiers and one girl at a border post opposite Russia
solemnly watched the Chinese national flag rise slowly at 7:04 a.m.
, the exact dawn of the new year here, accompanied by the national
anthem.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers released eight pigeons, symbols of peace, when the
flag reached the top of the pole.
</P>
<P>
This was the first flag-raising ceremony of the year 2000 in
Usu, the country's easternmost point, in Heilongjiang Province in
northeast China. The post is on the west bank of the Wusuli River,
the boundary between China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
It's an unforgettable moment for the soldiers stationed at Usu,
and for the seven-year-old girl, Zhang Longyu, seeing the new year
in this way, because they are at the far eastern end of China's
territory.
</P>
<P>
The sun shines over the vast snow-covered land in Fuyuan
County, as the mercury reads minus 30 degrees centigrade.
</P>
<P>
"I see the sun of the new year," the girl shouts excitedly,
rubbing her freezing hands, "I wish that the sun will bring good
luck to the motherland, and I wish all children study harder and
do better."
</P>
<P>
Although there were no fireworks and no dinner party, the
soldiers were too excited to fall asleep last night and they
invited the girl, their good friend, to attend the flag-raising
ceremony with them.
</P>
<P>
Usu is located at 135 degrees, 5 minutes east longitude and 48
degrees, 30 minutes north latitude, and most days is the first
place in China to see the sunrise.
</P>
<P>
But today, because of the season, the small town is 18 minutes
behind Shitang in Zhejiang Province in east China in seeing the
dawn of the new year.
</P>
<P>
 The eight soldiers and the girl and her four family members
are the only people living in Usu.
</P>
<P>
The small town is 60 kilometers from Fuyuan County, which
became an open port in 1992 with the approval of the State Council,
China's highest governing body. Since then, border trade between
China and Russia boomed.
</P>
<P>
 Post Commander Hu Tiezhu said that border issues between
China and Russia left over from the past have basically been
solved.
</P>
<P>
He added, "We hope that the Chinese and Russian peoples can
live harmoniously forever, and that the people of the world also
can live in peace and happiness in the coming century." 
</P>
</TEXT>
