<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Remote Seaside Town Revels in New Year Dawn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHITANG, Zhejiang, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The first rays of
sunlight of the year 2000 began shinning on the Chinese mainland
at 6:46 a.m. in Shitang, a remote seaside town in Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 jubilant tourists and local fishermen are
dancing and blowing trumpet shells to celebrate the new year dawn
in the little-known town.
</P>
<P>
A torch is lit on the high and steep cliff overlooking the East
China Sea, and the firelight blends sunlight amid the resounding
echoes of the sounds of hundreds of shells, creating a grand and
ardent ambiance for the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
As the sun rises gradually above the sea, more than 30 fishing
boats set sail with flags in the shape of dragons, phoenixes, and
tortoise hanging above their bows, flapping in the wind.
</P>
<P>
This little town came into the limelight soon after Chinese
astronomers announced last November that it would be the first
spot on the Chinese mainland to see the dawn of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Before this announcement, the town of Usu in Heilongjiang
Province, the easternmost point on the mainland, was thought to be
the first place that would cheer the new year dawn.
</P>
<P>
The 1,000-year-old town of Shitang is located at 28 degrees, 15
minutes north latitude, and 121 degrees, 36 minutes east longitude.
</P>
<P>
It has a population of 36,500 and covers an area of 16.26
square kilometers. Most of the local people live by fishing, as
they have there for generations.
</P>
<P>
The local government has decided to take this opportunity to
develop the town's tourism as one way to diversify the local
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Resignation Accepted by Sudan's President: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar al-
Bashir has asked his ministers and state governors to stay in
office after they expressed desire to resign to facilitate "
necessary changes in the executive power."
</P>
<P>
This was reported by the official Sudan News Agency (SNA)
Saturday. It quoted Minister of Culture and government spokesman
Ghazi Salah-Iddin as saying the Sudanese president did not accept
the resignation of any minister.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a celebration Friday marking the 44th anniversary of
the country's independence, al-Bashir said the ministers and state
governors had offered to resign, but he asked them to stay until he
could reform the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The resignations were called by the government spokesman as "a
self-motivated act that came after broad consultations."
</P>
<P>
Nearly three weeks ago, al-Bashir declared a three-month state
of emergency and dissolve the parliament, as a result of power
struggle with Hassan al-Turabi, the powerful parliament speaker and
secretary general of the ruling National Congress Party.
</P>
<P>
This was seen as a pre-emptive move to foil a planned parliament
vote on amending the constitution to drastically reduce the
president's powers, including the power to appoint cabinet
ministers and state governors.
</P>
<P>
The National Congress Party consultation group held an
extraordinary meeting last week to approve a recommendation to
bridge the rift between the two leaders, who had been on very good
terms with each other since al-Bashir took power in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The committee called for restructuring the executive body in
order to restore trust and tranquility. The resignations were
believed to aim at leave the president a free hand to form a new
executive body.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has already been beset by a civil war in the south, which,
coupled with famine, has killed more than 2 million people in the
biggest African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
