</P>
<P>
This was reported by the official Sudan News Agency (SNA)
Saturday. It quoted Minister of Culture and government spokesman
Ghazi Salah-Iddin as saying the Sudanese president did not accept
the resignation of any minister.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a celebration Friday marking the 44th anniversary of
the country's independence, al-Bashir said the ministers and state
governors had offered to resign, but he asked them to stay until he
could reform the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The resignations were called by the government spokesman as "a
self-motivated act that came after broad consultations."
</P>
<P>
Nearly three weeks ago, al-Bashir declared a three-month state
of emergency and dissolve the parliament, as a result of power
struggle with Hassan al-Turabi, the powerful parliament speaker and
secretary general of the ruling National Congress Party.
</P>
<P>
This was seen as a pre-emptive move to foil a planned parliament
vote on amending the constitution to drastically reduce the
president's powers, including the power to appoint cabinet
ministers and state governors.
</P>
<P>
The National Congress Party consultation group held an
extraordinary meeting last week to approve a recommendation to
bridge the rift between the two leaders, who had been on very good
terms with each other since al-Bashir took power in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The committee called for restructuring the executive body in
order to restore trust and tranquility. The resignations were
believed to aim at leave the president a free hand to form a new
executive body.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has already been beset by a civil war in the south, which,
coupled with famine, has killed more than 2 million people in the
biggest African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
