<HEADLINE> Cuban Government Considers 1999 a Fruitful Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Cuban government said
Saturday in a New Year message that 1999 was an intense and
fruitful year for the country in the national and international
field.
</P>
<P>
The government congratulated "our heroic people for the effort
made, for the results achieved, for the patriotism and the
firmness shown," in a text published Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The message extols the 41st anniversary this year of the
triumph of the Cuban revolution, and says that there were
significant achievements in health and education, while the Cuban
economy "advanced modestly in terms of productivity and efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the Cuban economy registered last
year a 6.2 percent growth, one of the highest in Latin American
countries.
</P>
<P>
The message underscores that there will be no end to the fight
for the release and the return of six-year-old Cuban boy Elian
Gonzalez, who is retained in Miami, United States, after surviving
the wreckage of a raft on which a group of illegal Cuban emigrant
tried to the United States
</P>
<P>
"Our goal will be to save him of alienation and crime, and to
return him to the bosom of his honest, patriotic, and
revolutionary family," said the message.
</P>
<P>
The government highlighted the work of the Cuban medical
brigades who assist the people in Africa, Central America, the
Caribbean, and more recently in Venezuela, where more than 400
Cuban specialists assist the victims of the rains in that country.
</P>
<P>
Cuba received the new millennium with tranquillity, without
mass festivities for the arrival of the year 2000. 
</P>
