<HEADLINE> Britain Holds Giant Millennium Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A giant millennium parade, billed
as the world's biggest millennium carnival, was held in central
London on New Year's Day with some 12,000 twirlers, marchers and
pipers paraded through Whitehall and along Millbank beside the
River Thames.
</P>
<P>
Gigantic inflatable cartoon characters pumped full with almost
70,000 cubic feet of helium gas floated past the luxury Ritz hotel
on Piccadilly and girls in silver dresses and sequined crowns
twirled vast multicolored fans.
</P>
<P>
More than one million onlookers -- mostly families with
children -- clapped and waved as 2,000 cheerleaders, 32 marching
bands and 75 floats and special acts paraded past.
</P>
<P>
With no reports of Y2K bug glitches in Britain so far, a banner
on a float which consisted of a caged computer in a reconditioned
supermarket trolley said: "Don't worry, we've caught the
millennium bug." The onlookers burst into laughter when seeing the
banner.
</P>
<P>
Blair congratulated police on their security operations which
he said had ensured millions of people could enjoy the millennium
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair watched the parade and said
he wanted to "bottle and keep" what he described as the country's
new sense of optimism.
</P>
<P>
"What struck me both last night and again today is this real
sense of confidence and optimism," said Blair, who watched the
parade after seeing in the New Year with Queen Elizabeth and 10,
000 travelers at the Millennium Dome on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
"You just want to bottle it and keep it," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
