<HEADLINE> HK Transits to Millennium Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong has a smooth
rollover to the new Millennium without any Y2K-induced incidents
reported, a senior Hong Kong government official announced
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
As at 1:00 a.m. Saturday, Hong Kong's Central Coordinating
Center (CCC), a region-wide Y2K monitoring and coordinating
structure, has not received any reports on Y2K-induced incidents,
Jessie Ting, deputy secretary for Information Technology and
Broadcasting, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The CCC has been in operation since 12:00 noon Friday to
monitor the rollover situation in Hong Kong and overseas. The
center works with coordinating centers of 13 essential services
sectors to respond to Y2K-induced incidents among different
departments and organizations.
</P>
<P>
Ting, who is also the controller of the CCC, said she was very
pleased to see that efforts made by all sectors concerned "are
bearing fruit as no Y2K-induced incidents have so far been
reported."
</P>
<P>
She said that in the next several days, the CCC "will continue
to monitor the status for each essential service sector and
coordinate emergency response to any incidents which have cross-
sector implications."
</P>
<P>
All government bureaus and departments with mission-critical
systems will conduct "wellness checks" for their systems over the
holiday, and report the result to the CCC, she said.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of these checks is to confirm as early as
possible whether there is any Y2K-induced failures in government's
mission-critical systems," she said, adding that if necessary,
they "will be able to carry out the required remedial work before
the first normal working day in the new year."
</P>
<P>
"Government bureaus and departments will also be required to
report to the CCC on the first working day in the new millennium
on whether their operation is affected by any Y2K-induced failures
encountered by their business partners, local or overseas," Ting
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
