<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Z. Opens Up Worldwide Millennium Celebrations(1)  By Zhou Cipu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand opened up the
worldwide millennium celebrations Saturday.
</P>
<P>
When most of the countries in the world were still in 1999, the
people of New Zealand welcomed in the dawn of the new millennium
with all-night carnivals, continuous entertainment, colorful
fireworks displays and devout religious services.
</P>
<P>
As the first country on the globe to enter the new millennium,
New Zealand's greeting of the first rays of the dawn attracted
huge attention from around the world. Its three official dawn
celebrations were live broadcast to about 2.5 billion TV viewers
in 130 countries and regions around the globe.
</P>
<P>
The three official dawn celebrations were held on Pitt Island
in the Chatham Islands, which is 800 km from New Zealand's east
coast; at Mt Hikurangi, a site of strong cultural significance for
Maori; and Gisborne, a city on the east coast.
</P>
<P>
Children took center stage in the first official dawn
millennium celebrations on the Chatham Islands, which consists of
two inhabited islands of Chatham and Pitt, and over 40 small
islands and rock outcrops.
</P>
<P>
The 50 people on Pitt Island and 700 people on Chatham Island
were the first communities in the world to greet the dawn of the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"Hi Millennium!" "Good Morning!"......a dozen of teenagers of
Pitt Island shouted greetings to the world from the top of Mount
Hakepa as the sun touched the first inhabited land at 4:59 am (New
Zealand Daylight Saving Time). They wished their greetings and
giggling, which echoed in the valley, could be carried far away to
every corner of the world, serving as an announcement that the
dawn of the year 2000 had arrived, thus raising the curtain for
the grand celebrations of the new millennium all over the world.
</P>
<P>
In the Moriori language, Hakepa meant the place which receives
the first rays of sunlight. Mount Hakepa is the highest point on
Pitt Island reaching 231 meters.
</P>
<P>
One and a half minutes later the children of Chatham Island
greeted the sunrise with a "Dawn Chorus" performance in dance and
song in which they "gifted" birds symbolizing peace, kindness,
hope and strength.
</P>
<P>
At the junction of the old and new millennium, a couple of
young people held a wedding ceremony. The first newlyweds of the
new millennium in the world promised to remain a devoted couple to
the end of their lives.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony involving Moriori, the first people to settle in
the Chatham Islands, a "Beacon of Hope" for the new millennium was
lit, beginning a series of similar beacons throughout the world.
The official midnight ceremony was followed by a dawn vigil which
culminated in a traditional Maori welcome to the dawn performed by
a local cultural group. This group also performed a traditional
Sunset Ceremony earlier to herald the millennium sunrise.
</P>
<P>
The Sunset Ceremony featured the four Touchstones of New
Zealand, which have been gifted by people in eastern, southern,
western and northern parts of the country to symbolize the ancient
soul of New Zealand. The four treasure stones were transported
onto the Chatham islands after travelling round the mainland of
New Zealand. Touching the stones, Islanders spoke out their dreams
for the country and its people in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Following the first dawn observances, the Chathams community
gathered for a communal breakfast during which the first horse
race of the new millennium was run.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Z. Opens Up Worldwide Millennium Celebrations(2)  By Zhou Cipu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The second site for New Zealand's millennium Dawn celebrations
was 1,752-meter Mt Hikurangi, 120 km north of Gisborne City. The
first light of the new millennium touched New Zealand's mainland
at Mt Hikurangi on the East Coast at 5:40 am.
</P>
<P>
Because of very limited safe space to assemble on the slopes of
the mountain, a limited number of people were allowed to attend
the celebrations there.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand Prime Minister Helen Clark, after attending
celebrations in Auckland, made a special trip to Mt Hikurangi to
join 2,500 members of the local tribe and their invited guests
including representatives of the other indigenous peoples of the
world in greeting the dawn of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Bidding their farewell to the 20th century, people held a
religious service to salute it by commemorating the deeds of their
heroes and heroines of the past. When the dawn of the new century
appeared, they made a traditional call of welcome to it, while
battery-powered helium balloon beacons atop more than 10 mountains
from Hikurangi to Titirangi in Gisborne City were lit. Under the
first faint rays of the dawn, the balloon beacons shined
brilliantly.
</P>
<P>
The devout people also chanted prayers of tribute. This was
followed by a performance of traditional Maori songs and militant
dances by a 500-strong cultural group.
</P>
<P>
Gisborne's official dawn celebrations attracted a large number
of domestic and foreign tourists, greatly outnumbering its 46,000
permanent residents. It was a combination of Maori spirituality,
contemporary dance, the concert with Dame Kiri Te Kanawa and the
New Zealand Symphony Orchestra and recognition of New Zealand's
place in the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The spectacular official dawn celebration, which began at 3:15
am on the waters and foreshore of Poverty Bay at Midway Beach
South, brought tens of thousands of people together. The
celebration started with a special Maori blessing. This was
followed by an interactive performance of New Zealand's journey
depicted in song and dance.
</P>
<P>
The most welcomed program was given by Dame Kiri Te Kanawa, the
most popular New Zealand-born opera singer who had immigrated to
England. About an hour before the sun touched the city at 5:43 am,
she began her performance for her hometown people, accompanied by
the New Zealand Symphony Orchestra. Her excellent performance was
warmly received and her sweet singing brought in the dawn of the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The sun was greeted by a traditional Maori call of welcome.
This prompted a host of canoes and the tall ship The Spirit of New
Zealand into shore. The celebration finished with a special
breakfast at a nearby place.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Clark hurried to Gisborne from Mt Hikurangi on
New Year's morning. She extended from the city new millennium
greetings to the New Zealand people and the people in the rest of
the world.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand organized hundreds of large-scale activities to
greet the new millennium. But the largest ones were held in
Auckland, the largest city in the country. As the first major city
to see the dawn, Auckland truly led the world into the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
A 12-hour-long, carnival style party was arranged in Aotea
Square and Aotea Center in Downtown Auckland. The party, featuring
Pacific Island's unique drumbeats and dances, traditional Chinese
Lantern-making and lion dance as well as a millennium ritual,
reflected the city's multicultural make-up and celebrated the
diversity of arts, entertainment and music.
</P>
<P>
There was a stunning theatrical extravaganza in the Auckland
Domain, the centerpiece of the city's millennium celebrations. It
was produced on a massive scale, with a 1,000-strong cast, state
of the art technology and special effects. The dramatic three-hour
journey through the past 2,000 years featured the birth of Jesus,
the rise and fall of the Roman Empire, the epic Maori canoe
journeys, Shakespeare, Newton, the world wars and much, much more..
....
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
