<HEADLINE> Beijing Not Bugged by Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, China's capital, has
not been bugged by Y2K problems, said vice-mayor Lin Wenyi early
this morning.
</P>
<P>
During the transition to the new millennium, there were no Y2K-
related technical disruptions in the city's major sectors
including power supply and telecommunications, the official said.
</P>
<P>
But she warned that all departments should remain alert in case
anything unexpected happens when all computers are restarted on
January 3, the first working after the New Year holidays.
</P>
<P>
Some problems might not emerge until well into the new year,
with February 29, a leap year date, likely to trigger problems,
she added.  
