<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Along Great Wall Pray for Peaceful New Millennium (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A children's choir sang a song
softly as a candle lit up the face of 55-year-old astronomer Wang
Jingxiu.
</P>
<P>
Wang, one of China's leading astronomers with the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, together with thousands of ordinary residents,
prayed for world peace as they converged on the Shanghaiguan Pass,
the east end of the world famous Great Wall on the shores of the
Bohai Bay, one minute till midnight before the first day of the
year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the world will enter an era of peace, democracy and
science in the new millennium, and China will become a most
prosperous, democratic and culturally advanced nation in the new
era," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
In ancient times, China presented to the world four great
inventions, including paper-making, gun-powder, printing and the
compass.
</P>
<P>
"I hope China will contribute still more to the world in the
new millennium," he said.
</P>
<P>
In response to the call of the United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), prayers for the end
of war and ever-lasting peace for mankind were uttered by Chinese
citizens along the 2,000-year-old Great Wall, a great wonder of
human civilization, like the pyramids of Egypt, the Taj Mahal in
India, and the Hanging Gardens of Babylon.
</P>
<P>
The temperature in Shanhaiguan at midnight dropped drastically
to more than ten degrees below zero. Seven-year-old primary school
pupil Ma He stood red-faced in the cold, freezing wind for more
than four hours.
</P>
<P>
"I'm too excited to feel the cold," the boy told his mother. (
more)
</P>
</TEXT>
