<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Chinese Along Great Wall Pray for Peaceful New Millennium (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Approximately 2,000 college students sang and danced around
campfires by the sea. Colorful fireworks that arced into the sky
and campfire lit up the camp site. Crowds gathered on the ancient
magnificent Great Wall, hills and seashores, waiting for the
arrival of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
When the clock struck the zero hour on January 1, 2000,
revelers on the Badaling section of the Great Wall in Beijing's
northern outskirtan area chanted joyously the final ten-second
countdown in unison, and at midnight more fireworks ripped through
the sky.
</P>
<P>
The sound of gongs and drums resounded from the Great Wall's
starting point at Jiayuguan Pass on the Silk Road in northwest
China to Shanhaiguan Pass.
</P>
<P>
People in China prayed for a peaceful new world on the Great
Wall, the only man-made structure visible from the Moon, which was
a means of defense against raids from northern nomadic tribes in
ancient times, and now is regarded as a symbol of national spirit.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 people from in China's mainland, Taiwan, Hong
Kong and Macao and from overseas climbed the Badaling section of
the wall. According to the traditional Chinese calendar, the year
2000 is the year of dragon, an auspicious one.
</P>
<P>
Fan Yunlong, a villager from Lingfen city of north China's
Shanxi Province, has spent three full years to complete a drawing
of 12 dragons on a 21-meter-long scroll as an expression to show
his best wishes to China in the year of dragon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
