<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eternal Flame, Big Bell Add Excitement to Beijing Celebrations ( Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Lighting a new eternal flame and
striking the world's largest bronze bell, revelers in the Chinese
capital of Beijing ushered in a new era.
</P>
<P>
 Gongs and drums, lion and dragon dances, flowers and laughter
filled the 4.5-hectare China Centenary Altar. Braving wintry wind,
the jubilant multitude awaited the historic moment.
</P>
<P>
 As a huge countdown board indicated only 20 seconds until the
year 2000, more than 20,000 people on the altar cheerfully chanted:
"Twenty, Nineteen, Eighteen ... Three, Two, One!"
</P>
<P>
 As the digital countdown reached zero, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin pressed a button, and a flame instantly leaped up from
the center of a square at the south side of the altar. The fire
will be preserved eternally.
</P>
<P>
 At the same time, people began to strike a 50-ton bell placed
at the east side of the altar, a memorial structure built for
greeting the new century and new millennium. Twenty one thundering
tolls of the bell echoed through Beijing.
</P>
<P>
 "The Chinese nation will be rejuvenated due to the motherland
's complete reunification and the establishment of a prosperous,
strong, democratic, culturally advanced and modern socialist
country," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
 Merrymakers set off an array of fireworks which spelled out "
2000" in the dark sky. Two hundred youngsters representing the
country's 56 ethnic groups, all wearing their traditional clothing,
danced delightedly. Nine dragon figures flying over the frolicking
crowd and a sea of flowers marked the gala's climax.
</P>
<P>
 History Professor Zhang Xiqing of Beijing University said he
takes pride in China's past millennium, during which the nation
invented the compass, printing, and gun powder, greatly promoting
the development of world civilization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eternal Flame, Big Bell Add Excitement to Beijing Celebrations ( Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Zhang is also one of the authors of the bell's inscription. He
said the bell is inscribed with 20 major events in China in the
20th century, including the Revolution of 1911, in which the
Chinese bourgeois toppled the Qing Dynasty, the founding of the
Communist Party of China, and the founding of the People's
Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
 Among these events are China's opening-up and reforms drive
and the return of Hong Kong and Macao to the motherland. The bell
also depicts the national shame of the aggression of foreign
allied forces at the beginning of the 20th century and the
Cultural Revolution from 1966 to 1976.
</P>
<P>
 "The past century saw China's rise from weakness to
prosperity," Zhang said. "History tells us that as long as a
nation works hard in unity, there exist no unconquerable
difficulties in the course of development."
</P>
<P>
 Flames lit the smiling faces of the people. The fire for the
eternal flame was brought from Zhoukoudian, 48 kilometers from
downtown Beijing. There, in 1923, archeologists discovered the
fossil remains of Peking Man, an evolutionary ancestor of man some
600,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
 The fire was brought to the altar by 1.87-meter-tall Dabenna,
a young man from Inner Mongolia who studies law at Beijing
University.
</P>
<P>
 "I'm carrying the sacred flame on behalf of all Chinese youth,
" the 22-year-old Dabenna said. "Like carrying the flame, we
should carry on the long history of China's civilization,
generation to generation."
</P>
<P>
 Looking up at the altar shaped like a giant sundial, Tang
Shaoguo, who took part in the building of the altar that combines
both traditional and modern styles, said China is certain to build
an even more prosperous civilization as long as it walks on the
right path, as it is doing right now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
