<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Fetes Dawning of New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Frenetic people around China,
one of first countries embracing the year 2000, overwhelmed the
historic sites in the country last night, celebrating the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
"To the future, the 5,000-year-old civilization is such a
marvelous gift," said Zeng Tao, a TV anchorperson.
</P>
<P>
Beijing built a new landmark, the Chinese Centenary Altar, to
link the past with the future, and a flame brought from the Peking
Man Site, where human ancestors learned to use fire some 500,000
years ago, was ignited at the altar.
</P>
<P>
At the stroke of midnight, President Jiang Zemin arrived at the
millennium monument which blends the symbols of the Book of
Changes, one of China's oldest classical philosophical works, with
modern technology, and expressed his wish that China will strive
to create a bright future along with the other countries on the
planet.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, crowds of people ascended the Great Wall despite the
severe cold, where fireworks, candle light and drumbeats replaced
the ancient smoke signals that once dominated this great fortress
built to stop invaders.
</P>
<P>
Other sites representing the ancient Chinese civilization,
including the Forbidden City and the Terra-cotta Warriors Museum,
were also jammed with Chinese, many of them returning from
overseas to celebrate the historic moment. At the stroke of
midnight, bells sounded in cities throughout the nation. "This is
the most auspicious sound," said Jue Xing, a Buddhist master in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Many believe that a new millennium signals the start of a
transition from chaos to order, and from separation to
reunification.
</P>
<P>
It was shortly after the beginning of the first millennium that
Emperor Guangwu expelled a usurper and revitalized the great Han
Dynasty. On the eve of the second millennium, the Song Dynasty
reunited China by ending the chaotic period of the Five Dynasties
and Ten Countries (907-979), and turned the Chinese capital of
that time, Kaifeng in central China's Henan Province, into the
largest and most prosperous city in the world. The first
millennium also saw the completion of China's four great
inventions: gun powder, paper, movable-type printing, and the
compass.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong and Macao, to the Chinese, is another
big gift. The 20th century began with cannon shots fired by
foreign forces attempting to split the country, but ended amid the
chorus of Beijing Opera and Western symphony orchestras under the
most brilliant spotlights. This joyful picture has undoubtedly
stirred up the nation's anticipation of a better century, and for
the reunification of China by solving the Taiwan issue.
</P>
<P>
The last days of 1999 passed as sales of private cars continued
to rise and people predicted a growing stock market in the Year of
Dragon.
</P>
<P>
After midnight, a general manager of a Chinese airline company
piloted a jetliner into the sky, showing his full defiance of the
"millennium bug." In Shanghai, citizens ascended one of the
highest skyscrapers for a first glimpse of the New Year sun.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the first ray of light fell on the Chinese mainland in
Zhejiang Province, and then went across the vast land to Tibet and
Xinjiang, two ethnic autonomous regions in the far west.
</P>
<P>
Many people believe that it is the time to commemorate the
giants. The names of Confucius, Laozi, Emperor Qin Shihuang,
Genghis Khan, Sun Yat-sen,Mao Zedong, and Deng Xiaoping appear in
morning newspapers in Chinese characters. The Chinese used these
characters to record history long before the birth of Jesus Christ,
and still use them today.
</P>
<P>
However, other traditions have died. In China, the years were
named after the names of emperors until 1911. The Western way of
calculating the years was not officially introduced until the
founding of the People's Republic in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Chinese civilization had in fact maintained a dominant position
in the world for thousands of years, and China has only lagged
behind the West for the past several centuries. Some observers
believe that China's rejuvenation began 50 years ago, and that the
new millennium will see the country take off once more.
</P>
<P>
At 23:59 of the last day of 1999, holding candles aloft, the
people gathered at the Great Wall began to pray for peace together
with people around the world.
</P>
<P>
The dawn of a new year had arrived in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
