<HEADLINE> Bells Ringing Far and Near As China Greets New Millennium (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the famous Beima temple in Luoyang, central China's Henan
Province, the two-ton, 445-year-old bell rang out loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
Perhaps no Chinese temples boasted more visitors today than the
famous Hanshan Temple in the east China city of Suzhou, Jiangsu
Province.
</P>
<P>
There, a 33-year-old Qiushuang monk timed his 108th strike of a
cast-iron bell to the clock ticking to zero hours on Jan. 1, 2000,
and thousands of people at the temple cheered as the last chime
sounded, rejoicing over the arrival of the new year and the new
century.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 30,000 clergy and laymen gathered at the famous
cultural spot today, including over 1,200 tourists from Japan,
Italy and other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
In China's largest commercial city of Shanghai, bells also rang
from the 70-year-old customs building, the Yufo Temple and Jingan
Temple.
</P>
<P>
"This year is really the high point of a century in which our
country celebrated its 50th anniversary, Macao returned to the
motherland and the new millennium arrived," said Monk Juexing, the
11th Buddhist abbot of the Yufo Temple.
</P>
<P>
"Bell chimes are the most auspicious and beautiful sounds of
Buddhism. I sincerely hope that the chimes will bring to all the
wisdom and good luck," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
