<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bells Ringing Far and Near As China Greets New Millennium (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- When clock struck zero hours
here today, the giant bronze China Centenary Bell, the largest in
the nation, chimed 21 times at the China Centenary Altar in
western Beijing.
</P>
<P>
From the altar, Chinese President Jiang Zemin pressed a button
to light the sacred flame, taken from Zhoukoudian on the outskirts
of Beijing, where the "Peking Man" fossil was found by
archaeologists in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after that, 20 people struck the bell in unison, to
the thunder of fireworks and explosive cheers from thousands upon
thousands of revelers gathered to celebrate the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The centenary bell, which was cast specially for the millennium
celebration, weighs 50 tons and is 6.8 meters high and 3.38 meters
in diameter. It is inscribed with the words to the national anthem
and accounts of the major historical events of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
Bells have been symbols of the Chinese nation for over 5,000
years. China traditionally rings bells during major festivals and
grand ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
With the advent of the new millennium, thousands of bells rang
across the ancient land. The Chinese people sincerely hoped that
this ancient and traditional instrument would spread their best
wishes far and near.
</P>
<P>
In the Chinese capital, the famous 579-year-old Yongle Bell in
the Big Bell Temple in northwestern Beijing boomed, along with the
"Zhonghua Hezhong", the Chinese Bells of Harmony, a huge set of
bells placed near the Forbidden City in downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
And from the Huangdiling in northwest Shaanxi Province, the
birthplace of the Chinese civilization, a 1.9-meter-high bell also
was sounded at the turn of the century.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
