<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant Bell Tolls to Greet New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, January 1 (Xinhua)-- The China Centenary Bell tolled
for the first time just as the year 2000 dawns in at the China
Centenary Altar where celebrations greeting new millennium started
minutes ago.
</P>
<P>
"One, two, three, ... twenty-one," people at the large altar
square cheered with great joy while counting the peals of the
giant bell. All together, 19 people from Beijing got to strike the
huge bell.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, showers of splendid fireworks burst into the
sky illuminating the entire altar complex and the jubilant crowd.
</P>
<P>
The 50-ton bronze bell is 6.8 meters high and 3.38 meters wide,
larger than the 579-year-old Yongle Bell, known as the king of
bells. The new bell is inscribed with scenes from major historic
events in China over the past century, the national anthem, and
the patterns of the Great Wall and the Yangtze and Yellow rivers.
</P>
<P>
A series of bells in Shaanxi, Henan, Shandong and Jiangsu
provinces, each at one of the four directions in China, sounded
simultaneously in response to the Centenary Bell to greet the 21st
century and the new millennium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
