<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Waves Farewell to Eventful &AMP; Successful Century (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The 1.2 billion people across
China greeted the turn of the millennium with a host of jubilant
celebrations extending from midnight through dawn.
</P>
<P>
A number of Chinese cities, including Hong Kong, Macao and
Taiwan, were illuminated all through the night with displays of
fireworks, laser beams, neon lights and candles.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, China's capital, more than 20,000 revelers joyfully
sang and danced around the China Centenary Altar, the only
symbolic structure built to greet the new millennium in China.
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and other Party and government
leaders joined the excited crowd.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said in a speech delivered at midnight that "the Chinese
nation will be rejuvenated due to the motherland's complete
reunification and the establishment of a prosperous, strong,
democratic, culturally advanced and modern socialist country."
</P>
<P>
A crowd assembled yesterday in Tiananmen Square, the heart of
China, to attend the last flag-raising ceremony of 1999. Tiananmen
witnessed the invasion by the eight-power allied forces in 1900.
It was also the venue where the 50th founding anniversary of the
People's Republic of China was held two months ago.
</P>
<P>
Hou Ruixiang, a 100-year-old man in Beijing, described the
first half of his life as a "unbearable period to remember." When
recalling the most profound impression in his life, Hou said, "I
enjoyed a happy and comfortable life only after the establishment
of new China."
</P>
<P>
Some residents in Nanjing, where Sun Yat-sen, the forerunner of
China's democratic revolution, is buried, climbed to the top of
Purple Mountain to see the first sunrise of the new millennium.
Sun led the Revolution of 1911 which overthrew the Qing Dynasty.
</P>
<P>
At the hometown of late chairman Mao Zedong, the founder of new
China, people lit firecrackers and staged a performance in front
of Mao's former residence.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, the first special economic zone in China, held a
grand float parade in its downtown today to express the great
hopes for the future.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, Shenzhen has turned from a small town
into the most dynamic powerhouse in China under the reform and
opening-up policy initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Waves Farewell to Eventful &AMP; Successful Century (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By 1998, China ranked seventh in the world in terms of gross
economic volume and ranked second both in reserves of foreign
currency and inflow of foreign investment. It jumped from 27th
rank in 1978 for total foreign trade volume to the present 10th
place.
</P>
<P>
Xi'an, a well-known historical city with a history of 3,100
years, held a series of activities to say goodbye to the 20th
century and greet the new one.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Tianyou, a historian, said, "Xi'an was the most prosperous
city in the world during the first millennium. It must return to
its former glory in the new millennium under the open-door policy.
"
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, which has made tremendous contributions to China's
economic take-off, organized a torch parade and a mass climb up
Jinmao Tower, the third tallest in the world.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Zhongli, an economist who participated in today's parade,
believes that Shanghai will become a leading international
financial center in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Macao, which returned to the embrace of the motherland 11 days
ago, and neighboring Hong Kong entered the new year amid fanfare
and millennium rejoicing.
</P>
<P>
"The return of Hong Kong and Macao to China were marked as two
of the most important events in late 20th century," said a Macao
sociologist. "At the turn of the century, we expect the hostile
situation across the Taiwan Straits to end at an early date."
</P>
<P>
Padanji, an 82-year-old man in Wuqia County, in northwest China
's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, and his 200 fellow villagers
were the last people to see the final sunset of this century on
Chinese territory, as the exact time of sunset in Wuqia was about
two-and-half hours later than it was in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
This once poor, remote village now has electricity and running
water. Preparations are underway to build a cable television
network.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that we will lead a better life in 2000 when the
gigantic acceleration of economic growth in the western part of
China reaches its climax next year," Pandanji said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
