<HEADLINE> Chinese Welcome New Millennium Along Great Wall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- As the clock ticked off zero
hours on the year 2000's first day, tens of thousands of Chinese
staged a traditional dragon dance and prayed for peace along a
lengthy stretch of the Great Wall, the beloved symbol of China, to
welcome the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Just before the advent of January 1, people from Jiayuguan, the
west end of the 6,000-kilometer-long Great Wall, in the desert of
the Gansu Province, across to Shanhaiguan, the east end at the
coast of Hebei Province, held candles and uttered a one-minute
prayer for world peace.
</P>
<P>
Revelers on the Badaling section of the Great Wall in suburban
Beijing chanted the final ten-second countdown in unison, and at
midnight fireworks ripped through the sky.
</P>
<P>
On the last night of 1999, people at the city gate of Jiayuguan
played traditional Chinese musical instruments to say good-bye to
the final sunset of 1999.
</P>
<P>
At 20:00 Beijing Time on December 31, 1999, Chinese on the
Great Wall let out deafening cheers and beat gongs and drums. The
jubilation passed from one tower to the next, until a total of 20
watch towers and ancient passes, symbolizing the 20 centuries
people have been through, were contributing to the roar.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of people participated in the six-hour
revelry, and over 10,000 Chinese and foreigners will climb the
Badaling Great Wall on the morning of January 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Bells Ring In New Millennium (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the ancient Chinese city of Xi'an, renowned for its
recovered terra-cotta warriors, the chimes of bells prevailed.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of domestic and foreign tourists beat on drums
fastened to their waists and danced the rural folk dance "yangge"
together with local revelers in the capital city of northwest
China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
In the east China city of Nanjing, the Alarm Bell, built in
1997 to mark Hong Kong's return, rang along with bronze bells from
various ancient temples, embracing the new millennium, and hoping
for the complete reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The central China province of Henan has been one of the
birthplaces of the Chinese civilization and it was here that the
first capital of the world was built over 4,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
When the first second of the new millennium arrived in Henan,
the set of bells that date back several centuries was sounded by
provincial officials, domestic and foreign guests.
</P>
<P>
Prior the sounding of the bells, more than 1,500 performers in
colorful ethnic costumes staged dancing and singing that reflects
the ancient Chinese culture and changes of the times.
</P>
<P>
Bells are auspicious symbols in Chinese tradition. The multi-
purpose musical instruments have often been used to mark historic
moments, used to symbolize merit and virtue, prosperity and
longevity, and other times rung as cautionary symbols for the
public.
</P>
<P>
Sounding bells at grand events and major festivals has been a
custom in China for thousands of years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
