<DOCNO> XIE20000101.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Bells Ring In New Millennium (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- As midnight fell on this ancient
land, bells large and small chimed nationwide to herald the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
In the famous Hanshan Temple in the east China city of Suzhou,
Jiangsu Province, a 33-year-old Qiushuang monk timed his 108th
strike of a cast-iron bell to the clock ticking of 0:00, January 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people at the temple cheered as the last strike
sounded, rejoicing in the advent of the new year and the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 30,000 clergy and laymen gathered at the famous
cultural spot today, including over 1,000 tourists from Japan,
Italy, Spain, Austria and the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region to witness the final countdown to the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Millennium celebrations are holidays for the whole world,"
said the monk. "The chimes are our best wishes for the human
beings, they represent peace and happiness."
</P>
<P>
Since 0:00 today, bells were rung in major Chinese cities and
tourist attractions to usher in world peace and prosperity for
China and its people.
</P>
<P>
In the capital city Beijing, three huge bells made specially
for the occasion rang.
</P>
<P>
One, a newly-cast 50-ton bell, was struck 21 times signifying
21 centuries, while the country's biggest time-service bell struck
200 times in honor of the year 2000. The Yongle Bell struck 108
times heralding good fortune and eternal happiness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
